{{About|correspondence rules in quantum physics|their role in [[philosophy of science]]|Ramsey sentence}}
{{Unreferenced|auto=yes|date=December 2009}}
In [[quantum mechanics]], '''correspondence rules''' govern the principle of replacing physical quantities with [[Operator (mathematics)|operators]].

Such replacements include energy and momentum, which can be derived informally from taking the time and space derivities of the [[plane wave]] function. These show a similarity to the [[heisenberg uncertainty principle]].

Examples of correspondence rules include:
{|class="wikitable"
! Quantity !! Operator
|-
| [[Energy]] ([[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|Hamiltonian]]) || <math>
i \hbar \frac{\partial}{\partial t}
</math>
|-
| [[Momentum]] || <math>
-i \hbar \nabla
</math>
|}

